%N A028461 Number of perfect matchings in graph P_{3} X C_{4} X P_{n}.
%C A028461 The rational g.f. and b-file extension were validated by an exact layer-by-layer transfer-matrix computation for P_3 X C_4 X P_n. A boundary mask records which of the 12 vertices of the current P_3 X C_4 layer are already matched to the previous layer; enumerating all matchings within the layer and to the next layer gives 924 reachable states. This direct DP reproduces the terms through n=460. Moreover, the order-83 recurrence holds as an identity of the full 924-state boundary vector at step 83, so it continues to hold for the DP sequence by linearity of the transfer. - _Steven Kotlarz_, Jun 20 2026
%D A028461 Per Hakan Lundow, "Computation of matching polynomials and the number of 1-factors in polygraphs", Research report, No 12, 1996, Department of Math., Umea University, Sweden.
%H A028461 Steven Kotlarz, <a href="/A028461/b028461.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..460</a>  (first 201 terms from Alois P. Heinz)
%H A028461 Steven Kotlarz, <a href="/A028461/a028461_3.txt">PARI/GP program for the rational generating function</a>
%H A028461 Steven Kotlarz, <a href="/A028461/a028461_4.txt">Python program for the rational generating function</a>
%H A028461 Per Hakan Lundow, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20171118074340/http://www.theophys.kth.se/~phl/Text/1factors2.pdf">Enumeration of matchings in polygraphs</a>, 1998.
%F A028461 From _Steven Kotlarz_, Jun 20 2026: (Start)
%F A028461 G.f.: A(x) = P(x)/Q(x), where P and Q are given in the linked PARI and Python programs as coefficient lists in ascending powers of x.
%F A028461 Q(x) is self-reciprocal: Q(x) = x^83*Q(1/x), and Q(x) = (1+x)*R(x), where R is palindromic, irreducible over Z, and has degree 82.
%F A028461 P(x) is anti-self-reciprocal: P(x) = -x^81*P(1/x). Hence A(1/x) = -x^2*A(x).
%F A028461 Equivalently, if Q(x) = 1 + Sum_{j=1..83} q(j)*x^j, then a(n) = -Sum_{j=1..83} q(j)*a(n-j) for n >= 83.
%F A028461 a(n) ~ C*r^n, where r = 145.5477203498858991690498096193638698200954885... is the largest real root of Q(x). The number r is a root of the irreducible degree-82 factor R(x); r + 1/r has degree 41. (End)
%e A028461 a(1) = 32 is the number of perfect matchings of P_3 X C_4 X P_1, i.e., of the graph P_3 X C_4.
%e A028461 G.f.: 1 + 32*x + 6345*x^2 + 862112*x^3 + 127027769*x^4 + ...
